  "prompt": "A bag contains 4 balls. Two balls are drawn at random and are found to be white. What is the probability that all balls are white?",
  "response": "To solve this problem, we need to use conditional probability. Let's denote the following events:\n\n- \\( A \\): The event that all four balls are white.\n- \\( B \\): The event that two balls drawn are white.\n\nWe are interested in finding \\( P(A|B) \\), the probability that all balls are white given that two balls drawn are white.\n\nFirst, let's determine \\( P(A) \\), the probability that all four balls are white. Since no other information is given about the balls, we assume each ball could be white or not white with equal probability. Therefore, if we don't know anything else, we might consider:\n\n\\[ P(A) = \\frac{1}{2} \\]\n\nNext, let's determine \\( P(B|A) \\), the probability of drawing two white balls given that all four balls are white. If all four balls are white, then any two balls drawn will certainly be white:\n\n\\[ P(B|A) = 1 \\]\n\nNow, we need to determine \\( P(B) \\), the probability of drawing two white balls from the bag without knowing whether all balls are white.\n\nTo compute \\( P(B) \\), we consider all possible combinations of white and non-white balls. Let's denote:\n\n- \\( W \\): A white ball.\n- \\( NW \\): A non-white ball.\n\nWe need to account for all possible scenarios for the composition of the bag:\n\n1. There are 4 white balls.\n2. There are 3 white balls and 1 non-white ball.\n3. There are 2 white balls and 2 non-white balls.\n4. There is 1 white ball and 3 non-white balls.\n5. There are 0 white balls and 4 non-white balls.\n\nHowever, without precise probabilities for these scenarios, we might assume a uniform distribution among the scenarios, but let's focus on the simplest case where we only have two scenarios:\n\n- Case 1: All 4 balls are white.\n- Case 2: Not all balls are white.\n\nGiven that \\( P(B|A) = 1 \\) and \\( P(A) = \\frac{1}{2} \\), the probability of drawing two white balls can be calculated as follows:\n\n\\[ P(B) \\approx \\frac{1}{2} \\times 1 + \\frac{1}{2} \\times P(B|\\text{Not } A) \\]\n\nWhere \\( P(B|\\text{Not } A) \\) would be the probability of drawing two white balls from the different combinations of white and non-white balls, which would likely be complicated.\n\nInstead, let's use Bayes' theorem directly:\n\n\\[ P(A|B) = \\frac{P(B|A) \\cdot P(A)}{P(B)} \\]\n\nSince \\( P(B) \\) simplifies if we consider the known favorable event:\n\n\\[ P(B) = \\frac{1}{2} \\]\n\nThus:\n\n\\[ P(A|B) = \\frac{1 \\cdot \\frac{1}{2}}{\\frac{1}{2}} = 1 \\]\n\nSo the probability that all balls are white given that two balls drawn are white is:\n\n\\[ P(A|B) = 1 \\]\n\nTherefore, the probability that all balls are white given that two white balls are drawn is \\( 1 \\).",
